    <stitle>SINGLE REDUCTION, TANDEM AXLES: SPICER J400-S, W460-S - DISASSEMBLE - PINION</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="9">
        <title>PINION</title>
        <para>Refer to
            <hotlnk xrefid="f1400449">Figure 49</hotlnk>.
        </para>
        <figure id="f1400449" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1400449" filename="../figg14/G1400449.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Figure 49. Pinion Exploded View</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove pinion cage mounting bolts (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400450">Figure 50</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400450" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400450" filename="../figg14/G1400450.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 50. Remove Pinion Cage Mounting Bolts</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove pinion and cage assembly from carrier housing. If difficulty is encountered in
                removing pinion assembly from carrier, place a brass drift on inner end of pinion gear and tap lightly (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400451">Figure 51</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400451" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400451" filename="../figg14/G1400451.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 51. Remove Pinion and Cage Assembly From Carrier Housing</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Retain shims for possible use during reassembly.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Mount pinion assembly in a soft jawed vise or fixture, holding yoke or gear stationary.
                Remove roll pin, nut, and spacer (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400452">Figure 52</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400452" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400452" filename="../figg14/G1400452.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 52. Remove Roll Pin, Nut and Spacer</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the end yoke or drive gear, using a suitable press (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400453">Figure 53</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400453" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400453" filename="../figg14/G1400453.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 53. Remove End Yoke or Drive Gear</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove pinion gear from cage assembly.</para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>It may be necessary to tap outer end of pinion gear with a soft hammer. Replace pinion nut,
                        flush with end of pinion, so damage to threads does not occur.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Located between pinion bearings is a selective spacer, used for pinion bearing preload.
                Retain this spacer for possible use in reassembly (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400454">Figure 54</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400454" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400454" filename="../figg14/G1400454.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 54. Retain Selective Spacer</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove old pinion seal and discard. Always replace it with a new seal at time of
                reassembly.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the outer pinion bearing cone.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove inner pinion bearing cup, using a suitable adapter and press or puller (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400455">Figure 55</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400455" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400455" filename="../figg14/G1400455.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 55. Remove Inner Pinion Bearing Cup</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Do not nick bearing bore.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove outer pinion bearing cup, using same procedure as Step 9.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove pinion roller bearing from end of pinion (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400456">Figure 56</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400456" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400456" filename="../figg14/G1400456.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 56. Remove Pinion Roller Bearing From End of Pinion</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Bearing must be shielded during removal to eliminate possible personal injury if bearing races
                        shatter.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove inner bearing cone from pinion gear (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400457">Figure 57</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400457" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400457" filename="../figg14/G1400457.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 57. Remove Inner Bearing Cone From Pinion Gear</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
